    <text>
        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Baltimore Nov 7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1883<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Mr. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>In answer to your welcome letter<lb/> I would like to write you all the new<lb/> things I have learnt in the last few<lb/> weeks some of them theories but the<lb/> larger number facts and when I say new<lb/> things you will understand them to be new<lb/> to me. My dread of the Germans is begin&#45;<lb/>ning to wear off and I can account<lb/> for Haupts conservatism from the fact that<lb/> Delitzsch was his instructor in Hebrew.<lb/> We over here&#44; like Luzzatto&#44; believe in<lb/> the Talmudic language and we find<lb/> cognate forms in other languages<lb/> We &#40;of<lb/>course I mean our Professor&#41; think  that &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> has no connection with  &#91;Hebrew&#93; but is either<lb/> from &#91;Hebrew&#93; found in Ethiopic or else the<lb/> Assyrian relative pronoun which is &#353;a.<lb/> The discussion which you mention as to the<lb/> comparative antiquity of Hebrew  &#38; Aramaic seems<lb/> to me to be a fruitless one. The most we<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>can say is that certain old forms which one <lb/> language has lost&#44; have been retained in<lb/> another&#91;.&#93;</p>
            <p>Could you give me any references or<lb/> information concerning  the word &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> I think it can be identified with the<lb/> Assyrian  Arax samma which  you<lb/> will re&#91;c&#93;ognize as meaning &#34; the eighth<lb/> month.&#34;¬ù I am already at work on an<lb/> Assyrian tablet and in Arabic we read<lb/> R. Saadia&#39;s paraphrase of Genesis. I find<lb/> Ethiopic&#44; thus far at least&#44; my most<lb/> difficult study. It is quite fortunate<lb/> for me that I read a little of the<lb/> Tarjam&#91;&#63;&#93; during the summer. It is almost<lb/> the same as Syriac and is very useful<lb/> for purposes of comparison.<lb/></p>
            <p>One of my classmates&#44; from Rome&#44; informed<lb/> me that the Library of Parma contained<lb/> a MS of the Bible of the ninth century.<lb/> Have you ever heard anything of it<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>from your friend the Librarian&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>We are to have an Oriental Society<lb/> here to meet once a week&#44; at which<lb/> special papers&#44; new books and the<lb/> magazines are to be discussed and<lb/> the University has appropriated two<lb/>  thousand dollars for Semitic books so<lb/> that our library will receive a con&#45;<lb/>siderable addition.<lb/></p>
            <p>I attend Schneeburgers synagogue&#44;<lb/> occasionally going to hear Dr. Szold.<lb/> I am told that Mr. Krauskopf is to<lb/> preach here next week&#44; but as he <lb/> will be at the Temple I shall<lb/> not hear him.<lb/></p>
            <p>With my regards to your family<lb/> and yourself<lb/>
                I remain Truly Yours<lb/>
                Cyrus Adler<lb/></p>
        </body>
